/*******************************************************************************
    Directives
*******************************************************************************/
    Directives are a tok feature that provides a means of inserting debugging code into a tok file as it is being compiled into C++. The directive code is written in tok and gets compiled into the C++ code that the tok compiler produces. The tok file is not changed in the process.
	The following incant definition of a directive shows how a directive is structured. In it incant fields making up the definition are:
            method is the name of a method.
            codeToInsertAtLocation is code, could be multiple lines of code, to insert into the method;
            location is a string (quoted if it includes blanks) matched against the beginning of code lines in the method. If the location matches: the codeToInsertAtLocation is inserted;
            where says where to insert the codeToInsertAtLocation relative to the matched line. The where field can have the following values:
                before              puts location before the current line (after is the default)
                starting            puts location before the first non-declare statement in method
                ending              puts location just before the } ending the method.
                within              if the current line is followed by a block delimited by {}. the code will be inserted after the {
            status can be: active; any other value means not active and the directive is skipped over
            #; marks the end of a directive.
    One final note on directives. They happen in order. If a directive matches in a method, the next directive searches thru the lines in the method for a match, looking ahead, not at lines already read. The parser is parsing lines of code, directive matching is done by the parser. The parser goes thru text, line by line, sequentially.

